(982, 1, '2021-06-04 21:47:26', '2021-06-04 21:47:26', '<div class=\"field-item even\">\n<h3>Theoretical foundations</h3>\n1. Algebra of sets and relations. Algebraic systems, models, algebras. Generating sets: systems of generating and systems of defining relations. Congruences.\n\n2. Monobasic and polybasic universal algebras. Structures. Lattices. Boolean algebras. Categories. Topos.\n\n3. Formal languages ​​and theories. Numbering of statements. Executable and general formulas. Gödel\'s theorem on incompleteness.\n\n4. Counting predicates. Normal shape. Erbran\'s theorem. Resolution method. Lambda calculus. The concept of redex. Church-Rosser theorem.\n\n5. Basic computational operators. Primitive-recursive, general-recursive and partial-recursive functions. Thesis Church-Turing-Post-Wedge. The universal machine theorem and the s-m-n theorem. Wedge\'s fixed point theorem.\n\n6. Algorithmically unsolvable problems. Stop problem. Church\'s theorem on unsolvable derivation recognition problems in numerous first-order predicates. Rice\'s theorem on property recognition.\n\n7. The concept of a finite automaton. Homomorphism and isomorphism of automata. Minimization of machines. Finished automata and their connection with regular languages. Analysis and synthesis of finite automata. Discrete converters. Systems of algorithmic algebras VM Glushkova.\n\n8. Formal grammars. Classification of languages ​​according to Chomsky. Syntax and semantics of formal languages. Algorithms for determining the regularity of grammar. Context-free languages ​​and their connection with vending machines. Chomsky\'s normal form. Greybach\'s normal form. Context-free language as a solution of the equation. Analysis and synthesis of vending machines.\n\n9. Top-down parsing. LL (k) -grammar. Recursive descent. Bottom-up parsing. Grammar of precedence.\n\n10. Discrete systems and tasks of their implementation. Examples of discrete systems. Counts. Petri nets.\n\n11. The complexity of algorithms and calculations. NP-complex and NP-complete problems. Gradient methods, heuristic search, linear and dynamic programming, coloring the vertices of the graph, the problem of the salesman.\n<h3>Architecture of information processing systems.</h3>\n1. Logical design and principles of the computer: memory and its addressing; processor, command system and scheme of its operation; external devices and the concept of a common bus; interrupt.\n\n2. Control of external devices: keyboard (checking characters in the buffer, reprogramming individual keys); display (cursor control, display of characters on the screen, shift of the screen and page); disk drives (reading the table of file placement, working with files); printer (setting print specifications, linking data to the printer); input / output (serial port access, device driver creation).\n\n3. Methods of organization and classification of systems of parallel information processing: combination in time of different stages of different problems, simultaneous solution of different problems or parts of one problem; conveyor information processing; systems with a single stream of commands and multiple data streams; systems with multiple instruction flow and single data flow; systems with multiple command flow and multiple data flow.\n\n4. The concept of computing. Multi-machine complexes: weakly connected, directly connected, satellite. Multiprocessor complexes: with a common bus, with cross-switching, high-speed RAM. Features of the organization of computational processes in complexes. Comparison of multi-machine and multiprocessor complexes.\n\n5. The concept of computer system. Systems with conveyor information processing; matrix systems; associative systems and cells; functionally distributive systems; systems with a restructured structure. SIMD and MIMD architecture.\n\n6. The concept of computer network and its structure. Network characteristics: operational capabilities, message delivery time, performance and cost of data processing. Processes. Control levels. Interfaces. Message structure. Protocols. Methods and means of switching and data transmission. Addressing, packet routing and data flow management. Transport service. High-level protocols. Administrative management. Local area networks.\n<h3>Operating systems</h3>\n1. Operating systems (OS): purpose and basic concepts.\n\n2. File system; external device drivers; command language processor. Command files. System configuration.\n\n3. Structure and functions of MS-DOS: basic I / O system; the initial boot unit, the module of expansion of the basic system of input-output, the module of processing of interrupts, the command processor; MS-DOS utilities.\n\n4. Organization of program interaction through interrupts. Dynamic loading. Download and run software overlays. Resident programs.\n\n5. Hardware, logical and software interrupts. Writing your own break; addition to the existing oneabout interrupt.\n\n6. Organization of multiprogram processors. Formation of processes. Software for computers and multiprocessor systems.\n\n7. Structure and functions of UNIX OS.\n\n8. Windows environment. Basic classes of windows. Controls, buttons, input focus. Objects. Scripting.\n<h3>Programming languages ​​and systems</h3>\n1. Procedural and problem-oriented languages: features of the organization and directions of development. Basic concepts and possibilities of Fortran, Pascal, Module-2, C, C ++, Ada, Lisp, Prologue languages.\n\n2. Translators (assemblers and compilers) and interpreters. Stages of translation: lexical, syntactic, semantic analysis, optimization, object code generation, compilation.\n\n3. Memory management in the program created by the translator: static, automatic, basic and dynamic memory. Geshing methods.\n\n4. Organization of parameter transfer between software modules. Call by value, by name, by result. Problems of complexing multilingual modules.\n\n5. Languages ​​that focus on parallel and distributed processing. Features of implementation.\n\n6. Generators of programming systems. Macrogenerators and extensible programming systems, preprocessors.\n\n7. Programming metasystems: multilingual systems, parametric systems and metatranslators.\n\n8. Dialog programming systems: purpose and architecture. Forms of dialogue organization. Ways of language communication: video forms, menus, spreadsheets, use of function keys, etc .. Dialogue in natural language.\n<h3>Software programming and design technology</h3>\n1. The main stages and stages of program design and documentation. Terms of reference. Sketch, technical, working projects. Implementation and support. Software life cycle. Cascade and spiral models of the software life cycle.\n\n2. Program specification. Conceptual means of specification. Denotational, operational and axiomatic semantics. Classification of specification languages.\n\n3. Software quality. Methods of debugging and testing programs, program verification.\n\n4. Organization of work of teams of programmers. The team of the chief programmer. Software production planning. Designing serial and parallel programs.\n\n5. The concept of recursion. Recursive definitions and recursive programs. Properties of recursive algorithms. Functional and recursive data structures.\n\n6. Structural programming. Theorem on structuring programs. Multibasic algebras of data structures. Theoretical-multiple data structures.\n\n7. Schemes of programs over memory. Algebra of algorithms. Software reuse. Modifiability of algorithms and programs.\n\n8. Object-oriented programming. Languages: Smalltalk, C ++.\n\n9. Functional programming. Concepts and examples. Lisp language.\n\n10. Logic programming. Examples of programming systems \"by the rules\". Language Prologue.\n<h3>Database management systems</h3>\n1. General idea of ​​the database system: schemes and instances of data, physical database, data model, data scheme, subscheme. Designing a conceptual scheme. Data definition language. Database administrator. Data manipulation language. Data independence; data integrity and types of functional dependencies.\n\n2. Physical organization of data: model of organization of external memory, hashed and indexed files, B-trees, files with a dense index, files with records of variable length; partial matching search.\n\n3. Relational, network and hierarchical data model and their implementation; model comparison.\n\n4. Data manipulation languages ​​for the relational model: relational algebra and relational calculus; algebraic and calculus languages.\n\n5. Theory of relational database design: functional dependencies, decomposition of relationship schemes, normal forms of relationship schemes; multi-valued dependencies.\n\n6. Thesaurus in automated control systems and information processing.\n\n7. Data dictionary dictionaries: basic concepts, use, design issues, implementation strategies.\n\n8. Distributed databases: centralized and decentralized DBMS; database distribution problems; execution of requests; simultaneous processing and updating.\n\n9. Database machine as a hardware-programmable multiprocessor complex designed to perform database functions.\n<h3>Knowledge-based systems</h3>\n1. The concept of knowledge. The difference between the concepts of \"knowledge\" and \"data\". Knowledge base. Knowledge base programming systems.\n\n2. Models of knowledge representation: production, logical, network and frame.\n\n3. Methods of knowledge engineering: formalization of knowledge, replenishment of knowledge and exclusion of redundancy, generalization and classification, deductive inference; Bayesian theorem, inductive inference, processing of incomplete information, fuzzy inference. Problem solving planning, analogy and deduction.\n\n4. Languages ​​and knowledge representation systems: concepts and examples.\n\n5. The concept of expert system and its structure: database; knowledge base; solver (output machine); knowledge acquisition component; explanatory and dialogue component. Formalized and informal knowledge.\n\n6. Application packages (PPP): models, functions, mode of operation, architecture. System and functional filling of PPP and intermodule interface. Modular analysis of the subject area.\n\n7. Decision support systems and features of their implementation.\n\n8. Stages of development of knowledge-based systems: identification, conceptualization, formalization, implementation, testing, experimental operation, modification. Tools and methodology for developing knowledge-based systems, classification of tools.\n\n9. Principles of hardware development to support knowledge-based systems. Lisp processors and Prolog machines.\n<h3>Literature</h3>\n1. Agafonov VN Program specification: conceptual tools and their organization. - Novosibirsk: SSh izd-vo \"Nauka\", 1987. - 240 p.\n\n2. Architecture of multiprocessor computer systems / edited by Timokhin VI - L-d: LGU, 1961 - 104 p.\n\n3. Aho A., Ullman J. Theory of parsing, translation and compilation. T. 1, 2. - Mir, 1978. - 620 с.\n\n4. Bar R. The language of Hell in systems design. - М .: Мир, 1988. - 320 с.\n\n5. Borisov AN , Vivams EP , Sokur L.Ya. interactive decision-making systems based on mini-computers. - Riga: Zinatne, 1966.\n\n6. Bratko I. Programming in the language of the Prologue for artificial intelligence - M .: Mir, 1990. - 560 p.\n\n7. Brown P. Macroprocessors and software mobility. M.: Mir, 1977. - 254 s.\n\n8. Bryabrin VM Personal computer software. - М.: Наука, 1968. - 272 с.\n\n9. Vagin VN Deduction and generalization in decision making systems. - М.: Наука, 1968. - 384 с.\n\n10. Wagner P. Programming in the language of Hell. - М .: Мир, 1983.\n\n11. Velbitsky IV Programming technology. - Kiev: Technology,\n\n12. Wirth M. Programming in the language of Module-2. - М .: Мир, 1987.\n\n13. Gaek P., Gavranek T. Automatic formation of hypotheses. - М.: Наука, 1984. - 260с.\n\n14. Glushkov VM Fundamentals of paperless informatics - M .: Nauka, 1962. - 324 